observations.recommendation:
a. Assess whether the PPAs originally funded are feasible to be implemented, otherwise may consider reprogramming to more suitable PPAs in consonance with NDRRMC-DBM-DILG JMC No. 2013-1, and other pertinent guidelines to encompass the four (4) thematic areas of DRRM such as disaster prevention and mitigation, disaster preparedness, disaster response, and disaster rehabilitation and recovery. Integrate them into the AIP for approval of the local Sanggunian to serve as a roadmap in DRRMF utilization;
b. Monitor the unexpended balances to be recognized under the Trust Liabilities DRRM account including its utilization and balances. Ensure the accounting and reporting guidelines are adhered to, based on COA Circular 2012-002 and RA 10121 known as the "Philippine Disaster Risk Reduction and Management Act of 2010"; and
c. Through the CAO, draw journal entries on the unrecorded PPE items in the General Fund books and be recognized with depreciation charges. Moving forward, ensure that PPE accounts are properly recorded in the TF books and transfer them in the GF once completed, issued to the end-user and ownership has been transferred in adherence to COA Circular 2012-002.

a. Through the Local School Board to assess the proposed plan to be included in the annual and supplemental budget and align it with the priority expenditures indicated in Republic Act No. 7160, as well as the DepEd, DBM, and DILG Joint Circulars No. 1, series of 2017 and No. 1, series of 2020;
b. Foster a collaborative partnership between the CGK and DepEd to enhance the budgeting and utilization procedures of the SEF, instituting control systems to ensure the efficient delivery of services; and
c. Consider lining up other expenditures besides sports development for strategic level decision-making and to effectively address the fund’s goal.

a. Through the Office of the City Accountant, adjust the affected accounts that are determined to be understated or overstated to present the correct balances and the necessary disclosures in the financial statements; 
b. Require the City Engineer to provide the City Accountant and GSO the necessary information for cost segregation of road projects; and
c. Prepare the necessary documents and submit the required reports to the Auditor’s Office not later than January 31 of each year.

a. Require the respective Project-In-Charge to (i) prepare Final or Terminal Reports for completed projects for submission to the City Accountant; and (ii) cause the immediate completion of the remaining projects. Make a representation with the source NGAs and propose that funds remaining for completed projects may be used to finance subsequent related project/s of improvement of the original projects already completed or if the said fund may be transferred to the General Fund as available for the LGU’s disposition, otherwise the same be remitted to the SA to be cleared from the books of accounts; 
b. Make a detailed evaluation on the feasibility of the unimplemented PPAs for which funds from the National Government Agencies (NGAs) were earmarked. If this implementation be proved to be doubtful or no longer necessary, may consider preparing a different request or proposal as a counter-offer before returning the funds to the source agencies (SA) otherwise, said funds shall be returned to the SAs; and
d. For subsequent fund transfers, timely monitor the implementation of PPAs in consonance with the signed Memoranda of Agreement (MOA) to realize program objectives beneficial to the community and avoid lodging amounts in the LGU financial statements.

a. Document accumulated experiences of communities from previous disasters together with inputs from concerned agencies like MGB and PHIVOLCS in updating the LGU’s Comprehensive Public Safety Manual, local DRRM Plan and Fund Investment Plan to design PPAs for the unexpended balances, and contingency plan to achieve a sustainable disaster management system;
b. Strictly comply with the accounting and reporting requirements embodied in R.A. 10121, COA Circular 2012-002 dated September 12, 2012 and COA Circular 2014-002 dated April 15, 2014 to ensure that the financial information is appropriately taken up in the books with adequate disclosures. The same reports shall be posted in the LGU website and full disclosure portal of the DILG; and
c. Recommend strategies and programs for appropriation for climate change adaptation and mitigation. Advocacy for the implementation of the building code and use of green technology, conduct of inventory, vulnerability and risk assessments for critical facilities and green technology infrastructure are to be included for building a safe, disaster-resilient and adaptive community.

a. Coordinate with the Local Development Council and Local Finance Committee to plan out feasible PPAs for the funds remaining and/or untapped; 
b. Evaluate the sufficiency and capacity of engineers and support staff to strictly supervise the implementation of PPAs; and
c. Require the CPMC to aptly conduct periodic monitoring and evaluation of the City’s PPA claims for payment for implementation with appropriate reports submitted to the City Mayor for perusal and appropriate action.

Directs the City Accountant to coordinate with the City Assessor and City Treasurer in establishing the accurate amount of basic RPT and SET Receivable from each taxpayer; 

Require the Accounting Division to set up and maintain an updated index card for each taxpayer to facilitate the establishment of the correct amount of collectible from each taxpayer;

Directs the City Accountant to effect appropriate adjustment on the affected receivable accounts by drawing a Journal Entry Voucher to adjust the amount of recorded receivables to reconcile with the general ledger balance and the amount actually collectible from each taxpayer based on the certified list of collectibles and reflected as the taxpayer’s ledger; and

Directs the City Treasurer to furnish the City Accountant with a duly certified list showing the names of the taxpayers and the actual due and collectible for the year which shall serve as the basis for setting up the RPT and SET receivables due for the year.
